article.description: Elton Brand totaled 26 points and 17  rebounds, helping the Los Angeles Clippers pull away for a 104-88 victory over the Minnesota Timberwolves.
article.headline: In his first start, Clips' Foulke limits Garnett
article.linkText: NBDL refugee Foulkes limits Garnett; Clips tame Wolves
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In his first start of the season for the Los Angeles Clippers, Tremaine Fowlkes had the difficult assignment of guarding five-time All-Star Kevin Garnett. Fowlkes who missed 11 of the Clippers' first 17 games because of a sprained right knee, limited Garnett to five points and three rebounds in the second half of the Clippers' 104-88 victory over Minnesota on Saturday. Fowlkes scored a career-high 15 points in 28 minutes. Fowlkes, a second-year forward from Fresno State, started 17 games as a rookie last season after being signed in February -- becoming the first player from the National Basketball Developmental League ever to start an NBA game. "I'd give myself a 'B', but the most important thing is that we came away with a 'W','' Fowlkes said. "You just have to be prepared mentally when you're coming off the IR, and I have no problem with that. I just have to wait my turn and make the most out of it when it's here.'' Garnett finished with 19 points and 14 rebounds as the Timberwolves lost to a team with a losing record for the first time in seven games this season. Garnett posted his league-leading 19th double-double with more than 3½ minutes still left in the second quarter, finishing the first half with 14 points and 11 rebounds. But he did not get a point or rebound during his eight minutes on the floor in the third quarter. "We can't expect K.G. to get 20 points, 18 rebounds and nine assists every game,'' coach Flip Saunders said. "At some point, other guys also have to step up and make plays.'' Elton Brand tied a season high with 26 points and had 17 rebounds for the Clippers, who have won consecutive games for only the second time this season. "We wanted to get the ball our of his hands, but we didn't execute well enough defensively and let him get into a comfort level,'' Saunders said. "We didn't handle the pick-and-roll very well or anything else that they were doing.'' Garnett helped trim a 12-point deficit to 90-84 with 6:36 to play, scoring his first points of the second half on a pair of jumpers in the lane 35 seconds apart. But Clippers rookie Marko Jaric kept the ball alive after missing a driving layup and Fowlkes' layup extended the Clippers' lead to 98-86 with the help of a goaltending call against Garnett with four minutes left. Keyon Dooling scored six of his nine points during a game-ending 10-2 run. "We made some big defensive stops in the fourth quarter, made some big shots, and that's what helped turn the corner,'' Brand said. "We've got some cohesion going now and we're playing the best basketball we've played in a while.'' Fowlkes skied above the rim and slammed down Andre Miller's alley-oop pass with 3:20 left in the third quarter to cap a 12-4 run and give the Clippers a 78-67 lead, their biggest of the game to that point. The Clippers, playing without injured regulars Lamar Odom, Michael Olowokandi and Corey Maggette, led 52-51 at halftime after Jaric cut around Minnesota center Rasho Nesterovic at the right baseline for a layup with 20 seconds left to help erase a nine-point deficit. "We just didn't execute our defensive game plan like we were supposed to, and we're not moving the ball enough,'' Minnesota forward Gary Trent said. "We're not all on the same page, from a mental standpoint and from a player-to-player standpoint.'' Playing their first afternoon game of the season, the Timberwolves were outscored 13-5 over the first 4½ minutes as Fowlkes made his first three shots on outside jumpers. But the Clippers turned the ball over three times in the final 47 seconds of the first quarter, and Minnesota capitalized with eight straight points to pull ahead 25-24.

Game notes
Garnett, who came within one assist of a triple-double in each of his previous two games, had five assists against the Clippers. ... The Timberwolves had talked with Cleveland about trading F Wally Szczerbiak for Miller before the Cavaliers dealt the point guard to the Clippers. ... Szczerbiak, who had a sprained toe on his left foot examined Friday at UCLA Medical Center, is not expected back for at least another two weeks.
